\begin_body

\begin_layout Title
Fertility, Household Labor Supply and Agricultural Production: Instrumental
 Variable Evidence from Uganda
\end_layout

\begin_layout Author
Bjorn Van Campenhout
\end_layout

\begin_layout Abstract
Fertility is likely to affect agricultural production through its effect
 on household labor supply.
 However, to uncover the causal effect of fertility on agricultural labour
 and production, one needs to deal with the fact that fertility is a choice
 variable within the household that is determined simultaneously with labour
 and production decisions.
 Using the fact that in traditional, patriarchal societies sons are preferred
 to girls, we isolate exogenous variation in the number of children born
 to the mother and related it to labor supply and production outcomes.
 We find that fertility significantly reduces the time women spend on agricultur
al activities.
 Especially land preparation and weeding seem to suffer when time needs
 to be reseved to care for additional children.
 We find that total production also reduces with more children, as does
 land area cultivated, while there is no impact on average productivity.
 Thus, high fertility means mothers have less time to work on the field,
 which means less area cultivated and lower productivity at the household
 level.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
At the most basic level, subsistence farmers in rural Africa combine natural
 with human resources to make a living.
 They use mainly household labor on their own small plots to produce for
 own production.
 As such, the quantity of family labor available is an important determinant
 of well-being.
 Family labor availability, generally believed to suffer much less from
 moral hazard problems, will be a direct function of the number of biological
 children within the household.
 For instance, more children means more hands to work on the field.
 At the same time, more children means mothers, and to a lesser extend siblings
 and fathers, will need to spend more time on reproductive chores meaning
 less time will be available to spend on agricultural activities.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Uganda has one of the highest fertility rates in the world and a substantial
 part of the population lives in rural areas making a living out of semi-subsist
ence agriculture.
 Even in the light of substantial reductions in child mortality rates, total
 fertility rates remain stubbornly high.
 On average, Ugandan women in rural areas bear 6.8 children over the course
 of their reproductive lives 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "New9"

\end_inset

.
 The question on how fertility affects well-being through its effect on
 household labour supply and agricultural production is therefore very important.
 For example, knowledge on how fertility affects time allocation by different
 cattegories within the household is important to gender-stream efforts
 related to crop intensification and commercialization.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this study, we will investigate the effect of fertility on agricultural
 production at the household level.
 In particular, we will look at the effect of the number of biological children
 on household member labor input, as well as a range of productivity measures
 for different crops.
 However, fertility is a choice variable to agricultural households.
 For instance, mothers who work long hours in the field may try to avoid
 becoming pregnant because this would only increase hardship.
 Or, households with low agricultural production may deliberately choose
 to have more children because this means cheap labor.
 If fertility, time allocations and agricultural production is indeed jointly
 determined, just looking at correlations will be misleading, and one needs
 to find a way to seperate the exogenous varation from the part that is
 jointly determined.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Our identification strategy is a simple but powerful instrumental variables
 approach inspired by the work of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "RePEc:aea:aecrev:v:88:y:1998:i:3:p:450-77"

\end_inset

.
 We use the fact that male offsprings are preferred in conservative, patriarchal
 societies to construct a range of instruments.
 The exogenous variation in the sex of a child can then be used to determine
 the exogenous component of household size.
 Such a two stage least squares approach is expected to yield consistent
 estimates for the causal effect of fertility on agricultural labor supply
 and associated agricultural production within the household.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Our findings suggest that, while simple correlations suggest a positive
 relationship, high fertility rates cause women to work significantly less
 on the family farm.
 Labor supply of men and children is unaffected by family size.
 Especially time allocated to weeding and land preparation are negatively
 affected by more biological children.
 We find no significantly productivity effects for most of the crops.
 Only for beans, there high fertility is associated with higher productivity.
 We find no effect on total productivity, as approximated by the value of
 the five most important crops per area cultivated.
 Both household level production and area cultivated are negatively affected
 by fertility.
 Take together, this means that more children lead households to reduce
 agriculture production mainly through a reduction in the number of acres
 under cultivation.
 The prime reason for this reduction is that women with more children are
 unable to free time to work on larger plots.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There is an active debate among scholars in the field of labour economists
 on the relationship between fertility and labour supply.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "RePEc:aea:aecrev:v:88:y:1998:i:3:p:450-77"

\end_inset

 use the fact that American couples prefer children of different sex, and
 and are likely to keep trying if the first two children are of the same
 sex as a source of exogenous variation.
 We will argue that in a developing country context, the sex of the first
 born child makes more sense as an instrument.
 Indeed, this instrumentation strategy has been used in such a context.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "doi:10.1080/00220380500356779"

\end_inset

 use the sex of the first two children to predict exogenous fertility in
 India.
 However, we feel it is too ambitious to relate fertility directly to poverty
 and related measures of consumption as there may be ways in which the instrumen
t can affect cosnumption besides through the fertility chanel.
 We therefore restrict ourselves to labour allocation and production.
 In addition, most studies that look at the effects of fertility on labour
 allocation are on data from Asia.
 Well documented high incidence of selective abortion in these areas means
 the sex of the first child or children becomes endogenous as well.
 This is likely to be much less of a problem in our application, which is
 to our knowledge the first such application to an African country.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This article is organized as follows.
 The next section gives a brief overview of the most prominent papers that
 are related to the present paper.
 Then, we make our case for the use of the sex of the first-born as an instrumen
t.
 We then present the data on which we will rely, and describe our main variables
 we will use in the analysis.
 We then present the results.
 In this section, we first take a close look at the first stage regression.
 We then look at the effect of fertility on household labor supply, considering
 differential effects depending on household demographics as well as agricultura
l labor activities.
 We then turn to the effect of household size on productivity.
 A final section concludes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
Related Studies
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Fertility and the related concept of household size impacts household well-being
 trough consumption and production.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "RePEc:ecj:econjl:v:105:y:1995:i:433:p:1415-34"

\end_inset

 focus more on the consumption side effects of household size in a developing
 country context.
 They note the contradiction between widely held views that larger households
 are often poorer (due to increased competition for a given food stock)
 and scale economies in consumption.
 The find that, if economies of scale are accounted for within households,
 the negative correlation between household size and consumption expenditure
 disappears.
 On the production side of the farm household, the effect of household size
 is equally ambiguous.
 Some may argue that larger households means that more labor is available
 within the household.
 The additional advantage of this labor is that it is not subject to the
 moral hazard effects often attributed to hired labor
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
For instance, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "RePEc:eee:deveco:v:18:y:1985:i:2-3:p:297-313"

\end_inset

 argues this may the reason why small farms appear to be more efficient
 than large farms
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 But at the same time, more dependents within the household means more time
 needs to be allocated to reproductive activities.
 Also, agricultural labour and agricultural production may be subject to
 diminishing returns.
 In this study, we will start by investigating the link between fertility
 and agricultural labour supply and then look at the relation between fertility
 and agricultural production respectively.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The relationship between fertility and household labor supply has been studied
 most carefully in the field of labor economics.
 Since this literature is so extensive, we only mention two of the most
 influential works here.
 The first is 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "RePEc:aea:aecrev:v:88:y:1998:i:3:p:450-77"

\end_inset

, who attempt to quantify the effect of fertility on labor supply in the
 US.
 They deal with the endogeneity of the number of children women have by
 exploiting the fact that Americans tend to prefer mixed sibling-sex in
 their household.
 They argue that parents of same-sex siblings are significantly and substantiall
y more likely to go on to have an additional child.
 They find that more children does indeed reduce labor force participation
 of women, but the effect is less pronounced than previous studies suggested.
 They find no effect on the labour supply of the father.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Another paper that tries to answer the same question is 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "RePEc:ucp:jpolec:v:88:y:1980:i:2:p:328-48"

\end_inset

.
 In this paper, the exogenous variation in the number of children is obtained
 by using the occurrence of multiple births (twins) at first birth as an
 instrument.
 The authors argue that the comparison between women who gave birth to a
 single child at first birth and women who gave birth to twins at first
 birth teases out the causal effect of related to an extra child.
 Since the occurrence of twins is exogenous, there is no danger that heterogenei
ty in women preferences contaminates the estimated coefficients.
 The study finds that household size reduces female labor supply, but the
 effect is only temporary
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
In addition to studies that investigate the causal effect of household size
 on (female) labor supply, there are also a range of papers that test Becker's
 quantity-quality fertility model 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "RePEc:nbr:nberch:2387,RePEc:ucp:jpolec:v:81:y:1973:i:2:p:s279-88"

\end_inset

.
 Many of these articles also use twins 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "RePEc:ecm:emetrp:v:48:y:1980:i:1:p:227-40,RePEc:tpr:qjecon:v:120:y:2005:i:2:p:669-700"

\end_inset

 and/or sibling sex composition 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "New1,RePEc:ucp:jlabec:v:28:y:2010:i:4:p:773-824"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "doi:10.1080/00220380500356779"

\end_inset

 use sex of the first two children as a natural experiment and find that
 household size has a positive effect on poverty in India.
 They use essentially the same argument as we will make in the next section.
 Our study, however, is are less ambitious.
 We feel that there are too many pathways through which household size can
 influence poverty to be useful.
 In addition, welfare, and the related concept of poverty, relies on consumption
 per capita.
 Consumption per capita as the independent variable is likely to be problematic
 in the two stage least squares setting.
 There is a real danger that the instrumental variable affects the outcome
 variable directly, instead of only through its influence in family size.
 For instance, if boys consume on average more than girls, the exclusion
 restriction is violated.
 They confirm that high fertility is correlated with poverty, but the correlatio
n dissapears when they account for potential endogeneity of fertility.
 There is also some evidence on Indonesia.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "RePEc:dem:demres:v:20:y:2009:i:26"

\end_inset

 looks at the relation between consumption and fertility.
 In 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "RePEc:iza:izadps:dp2162"

\end_inset

, fertility is related to the allocation of labour within households.
 However, they move away from the direct instrumental variable approach
 that is standard and instead estimate a reproduction function taking into
 account endogenous contraceptive choice.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
All the above studies employ data from South East Asia.
 It is well-known that fertility at birth is already skewed in many Asian
 countries.
 For instance India, from which 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "doi:10.1080/00220380500356779"

\end_inset

 drawn their sample, is particularly known for selective abortion of girls
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "New8"

\end_inset

.
 This suggests a relationship between the instrument and the error term
 of the structural equation.
 It is well know that, in the context of weak instruments, such correlation
 can seriously bias estimates 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "1995"

\end_inset

.
 The likely negative correlation between the instrument and the error term
 will mean that, in this case, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "doi:10.1080/00220380500356779"

\end_inset

's estimates are biased downward, in the direction of their original OLS
 estimate.
 This bias is likely to be much less pronounced in our data.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In our paper, we will try to address some of the above challenges.
 We will use the sex of the first-born and variations thereof as our instrumenta
l variables.
 We will relate fertility to agricultural labour supply and agricultural
 production, since there is a direct link between these three variables.
 We will also concentrate on Africa.
 Here, while there is a boy preference, reproduction rate norms are high
 and the cost of raising children is low.
 This means that selective abortion is much less of a concern.
 Still, we rely on the sex and numbers of children within the family, meaning
 that the kind of sex preference as described in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Jayachandran01082011"

\end_inset

 may still render our instrument endogenous.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
Boy preference and Fertility
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There is quite some evidence that parents prefer boys over girls in developing
 countries
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
In developed countries, there is a preference for a mix of sexes among children,
 as shown in, for example 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "RePEc:aea:aecrev:v:88:y:1998:i:3:p:450-77"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 For instance there is a large body of literature that looks at correlations
 between sex and variables related to well-being or quality of children.
 Significant differences in these outcomes are then considered proof of
 sex bias.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "New5"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "New6"

\end_inset

 look at excess mortality among female infants.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "New7"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "testit"

\end_inset

 investigate differential access to health.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "RePEc:oup:oxecpp:v:40:y:1988:i:1:p:32-54"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "doi:10.1080/713600059"

\end_inset

 find a correlation between sex and nutrition and 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "RePEc:ucp:jpolec:v:90:y:1982:i:1:p:52-73"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "RePEc:ier:iecrev:v:36:y:1995:i:3:p:795-818"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "RePEc:eee:streco:v:9:y:1998:i:4:p:453-468"

\end_inset

 all investigate correlations between the gender of children and education.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
However, at a more basic level, boy preference is already revealed by parents
 who, if asked in for example surveys, state clearly that they want to have
 more boys than girls.
 Such preferences lead to a particular decision rule with respect to fertility,
 where the likelihood that children are added to the household is positively
 correlated to the number of surviving girls in the household.
 The preference for a boy over a girl results in what 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Jayachandran01082011"

\end_inset

 refer to as a stop-after-a-son fertility pattern.
 There are many studies that show empirically that in settings with son
 preference, a couple that just had a son is more likely to stop having
 children 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "RePEc:spr:demogr:v:24:y:1987:i:4:p:517-530"

\end_inset

 or wait longer to have the next child 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "RePEc:spr:demogr:v:22:y:1985:i:2:p:145-168,New4,RePEc:spr:demogr:v:37:y:2000:i:1:p:95-108,RePEc:bla:popdev:v:27:y:2001:i:1:p:33-63"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Jayachandran01082011"

\end_inset

 argue that son preference leads mothers to breastfeed daughters and children
 without brothers relatively less long.
 This underlying consequence of sex bias my partly explain a range of outcomes
 observed in the area of health, mortality and possibly even educational
 attainment.
 Their model shows that even when parents want both boys and girls to have
 the same health and education, disparities can arise passively because
 of fertility preferences.
 They show that a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

try until you have a boy
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 fertility rule results in girls having on average more siblings, leading
 to more competition for resources within the household.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The use of the sex of first born as an instrument is motivated by various
 cultural and economic factors documented in the anthropological and demographic
 literature.
 In countries where no old age insurance is available, parents may choose
 to invest more in children that have a higher chance of being able to support
 them at old age 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "RePEc:ucp:jpolec:v:90:y:1982:i:1:p:52-73"

\end_inset

.
 Anthropological and demographic evidence emphasize the dominant role of
 males in traditional patrilineal societies where descent and inheritance
 are transmitted through the male line.
 Furthermore, male children strengthen the relationship between the wife
 and her husband's kin (by guaranteeing the continuation of his lineage)
 and secure (the mother's) access to residence and inheritance upon the
 husband's death.
 Also, the practice of dowry implies that a daughter is often associated
 with an expected expenditure, a central part in the theoretical model of
 son preference in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "doi:10.1080/00220380500356779"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Most of the evidence on boy preference comes from Asian countries.
 It is often assumed that gender preferences are much lower or even absent
 in Sub-Saharan Africa.
 This is surprising, as many of the cultural and economic factors that are
 observed in Asia equally apply to Africa.
 One study that documents significant gender bias in Africa is 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "RePEc:oup:restud:v:77:y:2010:i:4:p:1262-1300"

\end_inset

, who find skewed sex ratios at older age in favor of men.
 What is different from the Asian context, though, is that the vast majority
 of women are not missing at birth, but throughout the entire age spectrum
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The large effects documented in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "RePEc:oup:restud:v:77:y:2010:i:4:p:1262-1300"

\end_inset

 have recently been attenuated in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "RePEc:got:gotcrc:133"

\end_inset

, who confirm only missing young adult women.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "New3"

\end_inset

 argues that gender bias is likely not to be found at birth in the African
 context where high fertility is culturally valued and made less costly
 for families that still rely on the support from the extended family system.
 In Uganda, preference for boys has been documented in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "New2"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Even in Western societies, preference for the firstborn to be a son has
 been observed.
 For example, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "test"

\end_inset

 report an extensive list of studies that find men and/or women prefer a
 boy rather than a girl as their first-born.
 Even in the United States, the 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "RePEc:aea:aecrev:v:88:y:1998:i:3:p:450-77"

\end_inset

 provides some evidence of an association between having a male child and
 reduced childbearing at higher parities, in addition to the mixed-child
 preference.
 As such, we feel that the sex of the first-born (or closely related indicators)
 provide a valid instrument for fertility at the household level.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
Data and Descriptive Statistics
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We will use the Uganda National Household Survey (UNHS) 2005/06.
 While being somewhat dated, we have chosen this survey because it has much
 more information on agriculture than the more recent UNHS of 2009/10.
 Structured with a standard Living Standard Measurement Survey - Integrated
 Survey on Agriculture (LSMS-ISA) in mind, the UNHS 2005/06 collected detailed
 information on a sample of almost 43000 people in 7500 households in Uganda.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Ideally, we would like to have a sample of households where all desired
 children where born.
 A household that currently has one child may be in the process of adding
 more children to their family.
 Assume a couple that has just formed and is entering their reproductive
 stage.
 Assume further that the first child is a girl.
 In our sample, this household will show up with a smaller than average
 size, but with a girl as the firstborn, hence this may mistakenly be interprete
d as running against our hypothesis that households prefer boys.
 If the first child is a boy, this same household would show up in our sample
 as smaller than average, and thus this may lead us to put too much confidence
 in our hypothesis.
 The fact that we are working with a cross section of households rather
 than historical data on all births by women that have reached the end of
 their reproductive lives is also reflected in the average number of children.
 This is only 3.13 children, while women bear almost 7 children over their
 entire reproductive period.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To deal with this problem, we work with the difference in the actual number
 of children reported and the maximum reproductive capacity for a woman
 at a certain age, rather than simply the number of children in the household.
 To get the latter, we would need to estimate the average age at menarche
 within the population, and then simply divide into age the pregnancy period
 plus post pregnancy lactation in-fecund period.
 In addition, one would also need to corporate the maternal mortality ratio
 for "censoring" women's lives who have too many children and thus increasing
 her mortality rate (and exit from the sample).
 However, we took the 95th precental of total fertility rates per age from
 the Demographic and Health Survey of Uganda (2011).
 This is probably a good approximation of the upper bound by age of fertility
 in the population.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The selection of children is base on the household roster.
 In particular, we will select individuals that respond they are son or
 daughter of the household head.
 There is a potential problem when using a cross sectional survey such as
 the UNHS that only looks at reported dependents currently living within
 the household to calculate the difference between actual and theoretical
 fertility.
 Older women may be living in households where some of the older children
 have already left the household.
 Thus, at around the age of thirty, the gap between reported children in
 the household and theoretical fertility starts to increase more rapidly
 because of children growing old enough to start household of their own.
 More troubling, the reported gender of the oldest son or daughter living
 in the household may not be the gender of first-born.
 To overcome this problem, we restrict our sample to households where the
 mother is between 16 and 32.
 The cut off age of thirty two is because at this age, the first-born of
 the mother will turn 16, which is our entry age into the sample of mothers.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Looking at the sex of the first-born is only one possible strategy.
 One may argue that the sex of the first born is not very relevant in a
 context where women bear on average almost 7 children.
 Indeed, it is likely that households will get a second child irrespective
 of the sex of the first
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
This may especially be the case when target family size is large, as is
 the case in Uganda
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 This is supported by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Jayachandran01082011"

\end_inset

, who find that the difference in breastfeeding duration between boys and
 girls is largest near target family size, when gender is most predictive
 of subsequent fertility.
 Therefore, we will not only use the sex of the firstborn child as an instrument
 for fertility, but also experiment with alternative instruments such as
 an indicator that the first two children are girls or a variable that expresses
 the share of male children in the total family size.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Fertility
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this section, we will present some descriptive statistics to check if
 boy preference is reflected in fertility patterns in the Ugandan data.
 Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:gender-and-fertility"

\end_inset

 summarizes our findings.
 The first two columns checks if households that have a daughter as first-born
 are more likely to have extra children.
 We simply calculated the percentage of households that had more than one
 child conditional on their first born being a son or a girl.
 We find that in the sub-sample where the first child is a boy, about 37.46
 percent of households will have at least one more child.
 However, if the first child happened to be a girl, almost 40 percent of
 households will have at least one more child.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The third and fourth column present the same statistics, but now looks the
 sex of the first two children.
 As such, there are three possible scenarios.
 If the first two children are both boys, we expect that the chance that
 they have extra children is lowest.
