\begin_layout Standard
Columns (2) to (4) estimate the same models, but instrumenting size with
 a single gender related excluded instrument.
 In column (2), the instrument is an indicator taking the value of one if
 the firstborn is a girl.
 Accounting for endogeneity of fertility using the exogenous variation caused
 by the sex of the firstborn increases the estimate of the average number
 of days worked on the field substantially.
 A woman now reports to be working about 104 days.
 As expected, less time is spent on agriculture in urban areas.
 Female headed households now work significantly less days on the field,
 while more time is invested if the age of the firstborn is higher.
 Most interestingly, we now find that an additional child causes the number
 of days worked on the farm to decrease by almost 50 days.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Cycling through the results with the alternative instruments, the results
 change little with respect to significance.
 According to Hansen-J statistic, our model that uses multiple instruments
 is valid.
 We thus assume this is the best specification.
 This specification tells us that women spend on average almost 120 days
 in the field.
 Each additional child causes a reduction of about 60 days.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If we instrument fertility in the models for days worked for males in the
 household, average days worked also increases.
 Still, it remains much lower than the average days reported by women.
 Apart from the large female headedness effect, the only other variable
