 There are no fertility effects.
 Model (2) presents the same model, but instruments fertility with the indicator
 for the first child being a girl.
 This increases the average number of hour worked in the field.
 More importantly, the parameter on fertility now becomes significantly
 negative.
 An extra child reduces time spent on land preparation by more than 30 days.
 The effect is confirmed when we use both percentage of females among the
 children and the sex of the first-born as instruments (model (3)).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Models (4)-(5) run the same respective regressions, but now with time reported
 to input application as the dependent variable.
 The OLS regression indicates households spend less than half a day on this
 activity.
 There seems to be no significant effect of fertility on this activity.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Model (7) presents OLS results for time spend on weeding.
 If we do not properly model endogeneity of fertility, more children mean
 more weeding is done.
 Female headed households spend less time on weeding, as do urban households.
 Households spend on average 21 days weeding and each extra child increases
 this by about 2.5 days.
 If we do account for endogeneity of fertility, we find that household size
 actually decreases time allocated to weeding by more than thirty days per
 additional child (model (8)).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Finally, models (10) to (12) investigate the effects of fertility on harvesting.
 According to the ordinary least squares models, there is a significant
 positive association between the number of children in the family and the
 number of days worked on the farm (model (10)).
 The average number of days is about 17 days, lower than time allocated
 to both preparing the land and weeding.
 Each additional child is associated with an extra three days of harvesting.
 However, allowing for endogenity of fertility wipes out the effect (models
 (11) and (12)).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The above suggests that family size affects time allocated to land preparation
 and weeding in a negative way.
 It is interesting to note that the endogenity bias is largest for weeding.
 This suggests that households that have many children are likely to allocate
 more time to weeding (they may put, for instance, more children to work
 for weeding).
 However, if we separate out the causal effect that runs from household
 size to weeding, the reverse effect holds.
 Harvesting seems to be less related to family size.
 Probably, when crops are ready to be harvested, farmers are more likely
 to put in the extra effort.
 This seems to be less evident for work that has an uncertain payoff in
 the future.
 The reductions of time allocated to land preparation and weeding are expected
 to reduce agricultural productivity.
\end_layout

