\begin_layout Standard
In this paper, we look at the effect of fertility on agricultural productivity
 and its determinants.
 One of the most evident determinants is household agricultural labour.
 More children means more labour is available within the household.
 However, more children also means that time of the most productive persons
 within the family farm, adult females, is lost to reproductive choires.
 In this paper, we try to isolate the causal effect of extra children on
 household labour supply and production.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We find evidence that an increase in fertility causes women to work significantl
y less in family agricultre.
 We also find that family size affects time allocated to land preparation
 and weeding in a negative way.
 It is interesting to note that the endogenity bias is largest for weeding.
 This suggests that households that have many children are likely to allocate
 more time to weeding (they may put, for instance, more children to work
 for weeding).
 However, if we separate out the causal effect that runs from household
 size to weeding, the reverse effect holds.
 A policy based merely on correlations would therefore advise to increase
 productivity if the aim is to increase time allocated to weeding.
 However, in reality, the reverse should be recommended.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Looking at productivity of individual crops, we found a positive correlation
 between household size and maize, beans and sweet potato productivity respectiv
ely.
 Only for one crop, beans, this positive correlation seemed to be causal
 as well.
 Apparently, each extra child induces the household to become more productive
 in the production of beans.
 This suggests that household members, most likely mothers, try to compensate
 for their lost time due to child bearing by intensification of beans production
, which is one of the crops with the highest nutritional value amongst the
 five crops.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There is no effect on total productivity.
 At the same time, there is a reduction in household level production to
 increased fertility.
 This suggests that households with additional children, due to a lack of
 time, reduce the area they are cultivating.
