\begin_layout Standard
This suggests that reducing fertility as a policy in itself is unlikely
 to provide a sustainable path out of poverty.
 Households that increase production through area expansion (as opposed
 to increases in yields) are likely to stay vulnerable to shocks.
 Still, reducing fertility makes more food available at the family level.
